    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts, the relationship between GPU procurement and GPU depreciation, as well as the expected trajectory of depreciation as the AI compute fleet grows, is discussed in several sections:\n\n### 1. MD&A Results of Operations – Drivers of Increased R&D Expense (fiscal year and quarterly)\nThese passages explicitly link the build‑out of compute infrastructure (procurement) to higher GPU depreciation expense on the income statement.\n\n- **Year ended December\u202f31, 2025**  \n  > “Research and development … increased by $3,888 million … primarily due to higher **GPU depreciation expense of $1,673 million**, higher infrastructure and cloud computing expenses of $1,440 million **associated with the build out of our compute infrastructure**…”  \n  *(MD&A Results of Operations chunk comparing full‑year 2025 to 2024)*\n\n- **Three months ended March\u202f31, 2026**  \n  > “Research and development … increased by $1,471 million … primarily due to higher **GPU depreciation expense of $908 million**, and higher cloud computing and data center infrastructure expenses of $301 million **associated with the continued build out of our compute infrastructure**…”  \n  *(MD&A Results of Operations quarterly chunk)*\n\n- **Full‑year 2025 segment‑level driver**  \n  > “Research and development expense … increased … primarily due to higher R&D costs in our AI segment of $3,888 million **driven by the depreciation of GPU hardware and the cost of cloud computing as a result of our AI data center expansions**.”  \n  *(Segment‑level MD&A chunk)*\n\nThese statements indicate that as the company procures and expands its GPU/data center infrastructure, the associated depreciation charges immediately rise and flow through R&D expense, contributing to the segment’s operating loss.\n\n### 2. AI Segment Description – Expected Path of Depreciation as Compute Infrastructure Expands\nThe narrative that describes the AI segment’s cost structure explicitly ties future investment to a continuing increase in R&D expenses (which include GPU depreciation).\n\n> “AI segment’s R&D expenses mainly relate to the training of Grok … **These costs include … depreciation of data center assets, including processors**, equipment lease expenses, and networking equipment.  \n> **We expect AI R&D expenses to increase, both in absolute dollars and as a percentage of revenue, as we invest in compute infrastructure for Grok.**”  \n*(AI segment overview chunk)*\n\nThis confirms that the expected path of depreciation is upward as the GPU fleet grows through ongoing procurement.\n\n### 3. Property, Plant & Equipment Note – How Procurement Costs Flow to Depreciation Over Time\nThe accounting policy explains the mechanism: capital expenditures are first recorded as construction‑in‑progress (no depreciation) and then, once placed in service, depreciated, thereby impacting the income statement.\n\n> “**Construction in progress** is primarily comprised of ongoing construction and expansion of the facilities and equipment as well as **AI infrastructure that has not yet been placed in service**.  \n> **Depreciation expense** for the three months ended March\u202f31, 2026 and 2025 was $2,329 million and $1,237 million, respectively.  \n> Interest is capitalized during the construction period for significant long term construction projects, such as the **AI infrastructure data centers**…”  \n*(Notes to financial statements – Property, Plant & Equipment chunk)*\n\nThis illustrates the flow: procurement of AI assets (GPUs) initially sits in construction in progress; once the assets are placed in service, depreciation begins, and the depreciation charge grows as more assets become operational.\n\n### 4. Risk Factors – Gap Between Capital Expenditures and Near‑Term Profitability, Multi‑Year Investment Horizon\nAlthough not a direct numerical gap analysis, these risk disclosures describe the substantial capital outlays for GPUs and data centers and warn that these investments will lead to “reduced profitability or increased losses” over a multi‑year period – the effect of rapidly rising depreciation charges well in excess of near‑term incremental revenue.\n\n- > “Developing, training, and providing inference for frontier AI models requires **substantial and growing capital expenditures, including investments in specialized computing hardware, data center infrastructure**… We plan to allocate **substantial capital to build our AI compute infrastructure, and we expect a multi-year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA**.”  \n*(Risk Factors – AI segment capital intensity chunk)*\n\n- > “We have incurred significant capital expenditures and expect to increase … In addition, we have made and intend to continue to make **substantial capital expenditures to support the growth of our AI products, including costs related to obtaining third‑party GPUs, manufacturing our own GPUs, and constructing … data centers**. We may choose to increase or accelerate … which could result in **periods of reduced profitability or increased losses as we prioritize long‑term growth over near‑term financial performance**.”  \n*(Risk Factors – capital expenditures chunk)*\n\nThese passages connect high GPU procurement directly to future losses, which is the consequence of the depreciation cost flowing through the income statement before the assets generate sufficient returns, effectively describing the gap between capex and the timing of depreciation’s earnings impact.\n\nThus, the documents collectively discuss: (i) how GPU procurement costs are capitalized and then depreciated into R&D expense over time (PP&E note, segment description), (ii) that depreciation charges are currently rising rapidly as the GPU fleet expands (MD&A variance explanations), and (iii) that the company expects a prolonged period during which capital expenditures and depreciation will outpace the incremental contribution from those assets, keeping the AI segment deeply unprofitable (risk factors).',
